title: HAWQ-823. Initial Amazon S3 External Table Support
body:
Seeing some success using GPDB S3 external protocol support:

```
# On master instance
$ PGOPTIONS='-c gp_session_role=utility' psql postgres

postgres=# CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION read_from_s3() RETURNS integer AS                                  '$libdir/gps3ext.so', 's3_import' LANGUAGE C STABLE;

postgres=# CREATE PROTOCOL s3 (readfunc = read_from_s3);

---

# On segment instance
$ PGOPTIONS='-c gp_session_role=utility' psql template1 -p 40000

template1=# CREATE OR REPLACE FUNCTION read_from_s3() RETURNS integer AS                                  '$libdir/gps3ext.so', 's3_import' LANGUAGE C STABLE;

template1=# CREATE PROTOCOL s3 (readfunc = read_from_s3);

---

# On master instance
$ PGOPTIONS='-c gp_session_role=utility' psql postgres

postgres=# select * from pg_extprotocol ;
 ptcname | ptcreadfn | ptcwritefn | ptcvalidatorfn | ptcowner | ptctrusted | ptcacl
---------+-----------+------------+----------------+----------+------------+--------
 pxf     |     10888 |      10887 |          10889 |       10 | t          |
 s3      |     18881 |          0 |              0 |       10 | f          |
(2 rows)
​
postgres=# CREATE READABLE EXTERNAL TABLE S3TBL (row text)
LOCATION('s3://s3.amazonaws.com/goddard.datasets/osm_exerpt_ config=/home/gpadmin/s3.conf')            FORMAT 'csv' (delimiter '>');
CREATE EXTERNAL TABLE
​
postgres=# select count(*) from S3TBL ;
  count
---------
 3995735
(1 row)
```

In order to `CREATE PROTOCOL` - I had to access both the master and segment instance (only 1 in sandbox) using utility mode to circumvent the syntax check. Not able to run the test suite as it seems to be GPDB-specific.

HAWQ-768. Refactor c++ code for src/test/feature/lib.
body:
In this pull request, I refactored the code under `src/test/feature/lib` folder with following modification:
- Unify some C++ style: [The #define Guard](https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#The__define_Guard), [Namespaces](https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#Namespaces), [File Names](https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#File_Names)(I think we should be the same style with postgresql which uses underscores, but for makefile targets, we could use dashes), [Function Declarations and Definitions](https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#Function_Declarations_and_Definitions) and so on.
- Refactor the implementation of string_util, xml_util and hawq_config, which contain some potential risks of original impl.
- Fix the clang++ compiling warning in `sql_util.cpp`:

```
lib/sql-util.cpp:112:10: warning: moving a local object in a return statement prevents copy elision
      [-Wpessimizing-move]
  return std::move(psql);
         ^
lib/sql-util.cpp:112:10: note: remove std::move call here
  return std::move(psql);
         ^~~~~~~~~~    ~
1 warning generated.
```
- Separate the modification into three commits for review convenience.

NOTICE: the interface of `SQLUtility` and `HawqConfig` is unchanged. But user must specify them with `using` clause, check [this](https://github.com/xunzhang/incubator-hawq/blob/d55b160d1363831a3a49659d15400cb83f0d469c/src/test/feature/parquet/test_parquet.cpp#L6) for example.

title: HAWQ-738. Allocate query resource twice in function call through jdbc
body:
Root cause analysis:
1. It uses exec_parse_message and exec_bind_message and allocate query resource twice in parse and bind phases accordingly when using jdbc to call the function: SELECT public.fn_debug(). Thus query resource is allocated twice in function call through jdbc.
2. It uses exec_simple_query and allocate query resource there only once when using psql/libpq to call the function: SELECT public.fn_debug().

The resolution is to do not allocate query resource in parse, and only allocate query resource in bind.

Remove traceflag that allows ORCA to run in multiple threads [#118416…
body:
https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HAWQ-763
Story: #118416535

Our team is integrating VEM with GPOS memory allocator. VMEM is not thread safe. So, ORCA/GPOS also need to be single threaded. Currently, customers are using only the single threaded Orca.

In this PR, we are removing the traceflag that allows ORCA to run in multiple threads so that our customers do not accidentally run ORCA in multiple threads.

Refer to #117374177 for more context. Eventually we would GPDB to use Orca in a multi-threaded fashion to reduce query optimization time.

@liming01 @changleicn please merge this PR

HAWQ-708. Bump GPORCA to 1.630 [#117643411]
body:
-- 1.628 and rename EatMalloc to EatTracker

Better memory tracking.

-- 1.629 to include new GUC for Join Exploration

New GUC optimizer_join_arity_for_associativity_commutativity is added to
control Join exploration, hence speed up optimization time [#116333899]

For example, `set optimizer_join_arity_for_associativity_commutativity=x` will
hint at the optimizer to stop exploring join associativity and join
commutativity transformations when an n-ary join operator has more than
x children during optimization, pruning quite a bit of the search space.

-- 1.630 to fix CTE Predicate pushdown

This fix will prevent predicate pushdown with volatile function like
random(), which caused wrong result if predicates were duplicated.
